Exercise 1 (42 points).

Answer from Statistical Modeling: End-of-Chapter Exercises by Daniel Kaplan the following. I provide enough of each problem (Prob) or reading exercise (Read) so that it should be relatively easy to type your answers (text or code) in this file. I also provide some clarifications and hints.

Read 4.2 (5 points). How can a difference in group means clearly shown by your data nonetheless be misleading?

Group means can be very misleading when they don’t account for confounding variables. The example given in the text was that, at first glance, smokers seemed to live longer, but the smokers were also younger on average than non-smokers when the study began. Another example I heard (possibly from you) is that people from countries where cell phones are common tend to live much longer than people from other countries. But cell phones don’t actually make people live longer; cell phones tend to be most prevalent in more developed countries with advanced and widely available medical care. (I say tend to because America is obviously a huge outlier in availability.)

Read 4.3 (5 points). What does it mean to partition variation? What’s special about the variance — the square of the standard deviation — as a way to measure variation?

The variance is special because it’s able to partition variation— that is, it can tell you how much variation the model accounts for, and how much is still unexplained. This does not mean that your model explains the cause of the variation. After all, correlation isn’t causation.

  2. What is the group-wise mean of wage for females?

    ##       mean
## 1 7.878857

  3. What is the group-wise mean of wage for married people?

    filter(CPS85, married == 'Married') %>% summarise(mean = mean(wage))
    ##       mean

  4. What is the group-wise mean of wage for married females?

    filter(CPS85, sex == 'F', married == 'Married') %>% summarise(mean = mean(wage))

Exercise 2 (30 points).

Consider the height variable of the Galton data set. Further consider two models for height:
- model0 uses a single number, and
- model1 uses a number for each value of sex.
Residuals for a model are the differences between the data and the model. Variation can be measured in a variety of ways. Each part states what statistic to use for the model and how to measure variation. Calculate model0 values, residuals for model0, model1 values, and residuals for model1,. Then calculate the variations of the data, model values, and residuals. Does the variation of the data equal the sum of the model and residual variations for model0? If so, compute the percentage of the data variation that is accounted for by model0. Does the variation of the data equal the sum of the model and residual variations for model1? If so, compute the percentage of the data variation that is accounted for by model1.

  1. Use the mean for the models and the variance to measure variation.

    df = Galton %>% 
  select(sex, height) %>% 
  mutate(sex = sex,
         mod0 = mean(height),
         res0 = mod0 - height)

model1 = df %>%
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  summarise(mod1 = mean(height))

df = df %>% 
  left_join(model1, 'sex') %>% 
  mutate(res1 = mod1 - height)

df %>% summarise(var(height), var(mod0), var(res0), var(mod1), var(res1), sum = var(mod1)+var(res1), exp0 = var(mod0)/var(height), exp1 = var(mod1)/var(height))
    ##   var(height) var(mod0) var(res0) var(mod1) var(res1)     sum exp0      exp1
## 1     12.8373         0   12.8373  6.549134  6.288171 12.8373    0 0.5101643

    var(height) = var(mod0) + var(res0), so we can conclude that model0 explains 0% of the variation. var(height) = var(mod1) + var(res1), so we can conclude that model1 explains 51% of the data.

  2. Use the median for the models and the average absolute deviation from the median to measure variation.

    df = Galton %>% 
  select(sex, height) %>% 
  mutate(sex = sex,
         mod0 = median(height),
         res0 = mod0 - height)

model1 = df %>%
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  summarise(mod1 = median(height))

df = df %>% 
  left_join(model1, 'sex') %>% 
  mutate(res1 = mod1 - height)

ad = function(data) {
  mean(abs(data - median(data)))
}

df %>% summarise(ad(height), ad(mod0), ad(res0), ad(mod1), ad(res1), sum = ad(mod1)+ad(res1), exp0 = ad(mod0)/ad(height))
    ##   ad(height) ad(mod0) ad(res0) ad(mod1) ad(res1)      sum exp0
## 1   2.981403        0 2.981403  2.50735  1.99833 4.505679    0

    As before, ad(height) = ad(mod0) + ad(res0), so model0 explains 0% of the variation. However, sum \(\neq\) ad(height), so we cannot conclude anything about the percentage of the variation that model1 explains.

  3. Use the median for the models and the interquartile range to measure variation.

    df = Galton %>% 
  select(sex, height) %>% 
  mutate(sex = sex,
         mod0 = median(height),
         res0 = mod0 - height)

model1 = df %>%
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  summarise(mod1 = median(height))

df = df %>% 
  left_join(model1, 'sex') %>% 
  mutate(res1 = mod1 - height)

df %>% summarise(iqr(height), iqr(mod0), iqr(res0), iqr(mod1), iqr(res1), sum = iqr(mod1)+iqr(res1), exp0 = iqr(mod0)/iqr(height))
    ##   iqr(height) iqr(mod0) iqr(res0) iqr(mod1) iqr(res1) sum exp0
## 1         5.7         0       5.7       5.2       3.3 8.5    0

    As before, model0 explains 0% of the variation, but sum \(\neq\) iqr(height), so we cannot conclude anything about the percentage of the variation that model1 explains.
